AN  - 2358999597
AB  - After the election of Donald Trump, the Temporary Protected Status (TPS) community faced an uncertain future that pushed many to mobilize politically. As a Salvadoreña, I have paid special attention to how these changes affect Salvadoran communities in the United States. Since 2001, more than 200,000 Salvadorans had lived in the United States legally under the TPS program. As the name suggests, the program was supposed to provide temporary relief for Salvadorans fleeing devastating earthquakes that rocked El Salvador. As other national disasters, prolonged droughts, and gang-related insecurity continued to plague El Salvador, US presidents renewed TPS for eighteen-month increments. When Trump became president, the fate of all communities with TPS was under attack as Trump’s anti-immigrant rhetoric spread throughout the country. At that historical moment, TPS holders and their allies organized their community to take political action. Launched in 2017, the National TPS Alliance comprises more than forty local communities and organizations, including the National Day Laborer Organizing Network (NDLON) and the Central American Resource Center in Los Angeles (CARECEN-LA). The alliance has emerged as a diverse group of communities rallying to reshape the TPS program and challenge their liminal legality. Inspired by popular education values of solidarity and collective work, members of the National TPS Alliance have organized, lobbied, and marched to demand that the US government pass legislation that would provide a path to permanent residency. Individuals from the thirteen countries that once held TPS status have used various tools, including storytelling, to garner support from their own communities and their allies. At the same time, allies have held social media campaigns to urge their representatives to publicly support TPS extension. For example, #BakeforBaker encouraged residents of Massachusetts to bake a cake for Charlie Baker, the Republican governor, to support the TPS cause. By encouraging TPS and non-TPS holders, citizens and noncitizens, adults and children, the alliance has created a new movement of solidarity and action grounded in the community’s social consciousness.
